IMO... 

Growth Hacking = look for shortcuts, "hacks," or anyway possible to force growth. Sometimes legitimate, most times blackhats.

Growth marketing = set up mutually-beneficial processes, journeys, and strategic value- and empathy-driven tactics to attract customers and grow.

That's IMO :relaxed:

text:
Hey Susan, I personally view "growth" in this context in one of two ways:

1. *Growth as in speed* - Marketing tactics which have a short time to execution / see results from. One way I've seen this firsthand was me being a "Content Marketer" (slow to see results from my organic content efforts) and my colleague being a "Growth Marketer" (which was almost 100% PPC ads, and the tactics for which he was changing basically weekly).

2. *Growth as in scale* - Marketing tactics which "level up" the inbound numbers for a business (i.e. take it to the next level / drastically increase). For example, someone being hired to use whatever tactics necessary to turn, say, 50 leads a month into 500 leads a month.

text:
Here are two ideas:
1. *Branded letter boards.* Last year, my company partnered with a woodworker on etsy to create these beautiful letter boards and recipients have taken a lot of pride in using them to express themselves, sharing about it both online and IRL. We get a lot of mileage there. The takeaway: when brainstorming, we tried to think about what kinds of trends people were going nuts over and how we might be able to hop on them. People love motivational stuff and letter boards were having a (long) moment. (If you use this idea for your article, do me a solid and don’t include my image.)
2. *Branded Field Notes iconic <https://fieldnotesbrand.com/customization|memo books>.* I pitched this to an adventure travel client and they told me they felt s_een_. The takeaway: it was a simple offering, but insightful in a way that spoke directly to their audience’s soul. (Field Notes team was excellent to work with, too.)
